{"branch":"main","confidence":95,"prompt":"## CHOSEN: Custom Fiber Data Structure with Cooperative Scheduling

### Source
Issue #7942 "Fiber Principles: Contributing To Fiber"
https://github.com/facebook/react/issues/7942

### Author
Sebastian Markbåge (@sebmarkbage)
Date: October 11, 2016

### The Fiber Architecture - Core Design Principles

From the issue body:

> "I just wanted to document a few unique design patterns that apply to Fiber, but not necessarily anything else."

#### 1. Two-Phase Rendering (No Side Effects During Work)
> "You may mutate the fiber that you're working on during `beginWork` and `completeWork` phases but you may not have any other global side-effects. If you need a global side-effect, that have to be moved to the `commitWork` phase."

#### 2. Fixed Data Structure (Performance)
> "Fiber is a fixed data structure. It shares the same hidden class. Never add fields outside of construction in `ReactFiber`."

#### 3. No Dynamic Dispatch (Optimization)
> "Nothing in the reconciler uses dynamic dispatch. I.e. we don't call a first class function, except for user code such as ref callbacks, functional components, render methods, etc. The rest is a static function available in a closure. I.e. use `myHelper(obj)` instead of `obj.myHelper()`. Any time we need to branch logic we use a switch statement over a `tag` which is a number."

#### 4. No JS Stack Recursion (Enables Yielding)
> "Nothing in Fiber uses the normal JS stack. Meaning it does use the stack but it can be compiled into a flat function if needed. Calling other functions is fine - the only limitation is that they can't be recursive."

#### 5. Singly-Linked List Traversal Algorithm
> "If I can't use recursion, how do I traverse through the tree? Learn to use the singly linked list tree traversal algorithm."

```js
let root = fiber;
let node = fiber;
while (true) {
  // Do something with node
  if (node.child) {
    node = node.child;
    continue;
  }
  if (node === root) {
    return;
  }
  while (!node.sibling) {
    if (!node.return || node.return === root) {
      return;
    }
    node = node.return;
  }
  node = node.sibling;
}
```

### Why This Design Wins

> "We can use the normal JS stack for this but any time we yield in a `requestIdleCallback` we would have to rebuild the stack when we continue. Since this only lasts for about 50ms when idle, we would spend some time unwinding and rebuilding the stack each time."

> "Most of what React does is in the space of what the normal stack does. E.g. memoization, error handling, etc. Using the normal stack too, just makes it more difficult to get those to interact."

> "Everything we put on the stack we generally have to put on the heap too because we memoize it. Maintaining the stack and the heap with the same data is theoretically less efficient."

### Key Benefits Achieved
1. **Interruptible**: Can pause at any fiber node
2. **Resumable**: Can continue from where we left off
3. **Prioritizable**: Different work can have different priorities
4. **Memoizable**: Can skip unchanged subtrees
5. **Abortable**: Can throw away work-in-progress if higher priority work arrives

### Related Links
- Issue #6170 "New Core Algorithm": https://github.com/facebook/react/issues/6170
- Issue #7925 "Fiber Umbrella": https://github.com/facebook/react/issues/7925
- Andrew Clark's Fiber Architecture doc: https://github.com/acdlite/react-fiber-architecture"}

{"branch":"main","confidence":95,"prompt":"useTransition and startTransition - The Lanes Model in Action

From React 18 changelog:
"startTransition and useTransition let you mark some state updates as not urgent. Other state updates are considered urgent by default. React will allow urgent state updates (for example, updating a text input) to interrupt non-urgent state updates (for example, rendering a list of search results)."

WHY this matters:
- Before: All state updates had equal priority
- User typing would be blocked by expensive re-renders
- No way to say "this update can wait, this one is urgent"

How it works with Lanes:
- Urgent updates get SyncLane (highest priority)
- Transition updates get TransitionLane (can be interrupted)
- React schedules work based on lane priority
- Urgent work can interrupt transition work

Usage:
const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();
startTransition(() => {
  setSearchResults(expensiveFilter(query));
});
// isPending shows if transition is still pending

This is the user-facing API that exposes Fiber's interruptible rendering capability.

PRs: #10426, #10715, #15593, #15272, #15578, #15769, #17058, #18796, #19121, #19703, #19719, #19724, #20672, #20976

Authors: @acdlite, @lunaruan, @rickhanlonii, @sebmarkbage"}

{"branch":"main","confidence":95,"prompt":"Automatic Batching - Fewer Renders in React 18

From React 18 changelog:
"Automatic batching: This release introduces a performance improvement that changes to the way React batches updates to do more batching automatically."

Discussion: https://github.com/reactwg/react-18/discussions/21

Before React 18:
- Only updates inside React event handlers were batched
- Updates in timeouts, promises, native event handlers were NOT batched
- Each setState caused a separate re-render

React 18:
- ALL updates are batched by default, regardless of where they originate
- Updates in promises, setTimeout, native event handlers are now batched
- Use flushSync() to opt out if needed

WHY this matters for reconciler:
- Reduces number of reconciliation passes
- More efficient use of Fiber's work loop
- Consistent behavior regardless of update source

Example:
// Before React 18: Two re-renders
setTimeout(() => {
  setCount(c => c + 1);  // Render 1
  setFlag(f => !f);      // Render 2
}, 1000);

// React 18: One re-render (both batched)
setTimeout(() => {
  setCount(c => c + 1);
  setFlag(f => !f);      // Single batched render
}, 1000);"}
